"# Appendix A ‚Äî Reference-manual anatomy: the SLAT schema of a verb record

Every verb record in the reference manual is a SLAT s-expression with a fixed field set. This appendix documents the schema. Use it as a reference when reading or generating records.

## A.1 The full schema

```scheme
(verb
  :name          string              ;; required ‚Äî the verb's registered name
  :doc           string              ;; one-sentence imperative description
  :contract      string              ;; signature, e.g. \"(pair) -> any\"
  :arity         integer-or-list     ;; N, or (min max), or 'variadic
  :examples      list                ;; list of (:level :code) records
  :namespace     string-or-nil       ;; e.g. \"cortex\", or nil for base
  :tier          string              ;; \"core\" | \"extended\" | \"experimental\"
  :perm          string              ;; closed vocabulary of 8 tiers
  :atom          string-or-nil       ;; fine-grained category grouping
  :source        string-or-nil       ;; path:line pointing at impl
  :since         string-or-nil       ;; version when verb was added
  :confirm       boolean             ;; dispatcher gate
  :rateLimit     string-or-nil       ;; e.g. \"1/30s\"
  :schema        function-or-nil     ;; validator: (args) -> #t or error-string
  :idempotent    boolean             ;; dispatcher dedupes when true
  :powerTier     string              ;; \"always\" | \"paint\" | \"animate\" | \"full-power\"
  :chip          string-or-nil       ;; auto-emit chip kind
  :deprecated    boolean             ;; if true, prefer :aliasFor
  :aliasFor      string-or-nil       ;; canonical name this aliases
  :examples-arc  string-or-nil       ;; optional pedagogical arc description
)
```

Twenty fields. The first eleven are what `help` returns. The next eight are dispatcher-facing. `:examples-arc` is optional metadata for teaching context.

## A.2 Field-by-field

### :name

Required. String. The name the verb is registered under. This is what the dispatcher looks up when a caller invokes the verb. Also what `help` and every other introspection verb use as the primary key.

Convention: lowercase, hyphens between words, optional namespace prefix with `/`. Examples: `car`, `map`, `cortex/query`, `card/open`, `composer/piano-roll`.

### :doc

String. One sentence in imperative mood ending in a period. This is the primary human-readable description.

Style: `\"Return the first element of a pair.\"` Not `\"Returns...\"` (present-continuous is dispreferred). Not `\"A function that returns...\"` (frame is unnecessary).

If a verb has no doc, `doc-of` returns nil and the reader has no summary. Every published verb should have a doc.

### :contract

String. A signature mini-language description of the verb's shape.

Grammar (informal):
- `(a b c) -> d` ‚Äî takes three args of shapes a, b, c; returns shape d
- `(a b?)` ‚Äî b is optional
- `(a ...)` ‚Äî variadic in a
- `(:key val)` ‚Äî keyword-plist argument
- `X | Y` ‚Äî union type

The mini-language is not enforced at runtime. It documents the intended shape.

### :arity

Integer, list, or symbol. Encodes argument count.

- Integer N ‚Äî takes exactly N arguments
- List `(min max)` ‚Äî takes between min and max
- Symbol `'variadic` ‚Äî takes any number

Used by the dispatcher for arity-mismatch errors.

### :examples

List of records. Each record is a plist with `:level` and `:code`.

- `:level` ‚Äî one of `novice`, `intermediate`, `expert`
- `:code` ‚Äî a runnable Scheme expression as a string

Ideally three examples per verb, one per level. Feeds the LLM training corpus.

## A.3 Namespace, tier, perm, atom

### :namespace

Optional string. Prefix grouping the verb belongs to. Examples: `\"cortex\"`, `\"card\"`, `\"composer\"`, `\"paint\"`. Nil for base verbs without a prefix.

### :tier

String. One of `\"core\"`, `\"extended\"`, `\"experimental\"`.

- `core` ‚Äî frozen, never changes
- `extended` ‚Äî stable but not yet trained on; may evolve
- `experimental` ‚Äî may change name or arity

### :perm

String. Closed vocabulary:

- `read` ‚Äî pure observation
- `paint` ‚Äî visual side effects only
- `animate` ‚Äî motion or RAF tween
- `state-change` ‚Äî moves UI or persists state
- `destructive` ‚Äî deletes or transfers
- `financial` ‚Äî money moves
- `network` ‚Äî outbound network call
- `personal-data` ‚Äî reads/writes user PII

Enforced by the dispatcher.

### :atom

Optional string. Fine-grained category for reference-manual TOC grouping. Examples: `\"paint-primitive\"`, `\"synth-note\"`, `\"card-lifecycle\"`. Nil for verbs in the general pool.

## A.4 Source, since

### :source

Optional string. Format `path:line`. Path is relative to runtime root. Line is 1-indexed.

Manually maintained; may drift when implementations move within a file.

### :since

Optional string. Version tag when the verb was added. Examples: `\"1.0\"`, `\"1.4\"`, `\"1.5-experimental\"`.

Useful for release notes generation and durability audits.

## A.5 Dispatcher fields

### :confirm

Boolean. If true, dispatcher requires the caller to have set `caller.confirmed` before allowing the call. Used for verbs that need explicit user confirmation (e.g., destructive operations).

### :rateLimit

Optional string. Format `<count>/<duration>` like `\"1/30s\"` or `\"10/min\"`. Dispatcher tracks call frequency per caller and refuses if the rate is exceeded.

### :schema

Optional function `(args) -> #t | error-string`. Called by dispatcher before the verb runs. Returns `#t` to pass, an error message string to reject.

Runtime type-check hook. Not populated for most verbs.

### :idempotent

Boolean. If true, dispatcher dedupes recent calls ‚Äî a second call with the same args within a short window returns the cached result without re-invoking the verb.

Useful for verbs that are pure functions of their input and expensive to compute.

### :powerTier

String. Substrate power gate. One of `always`, `paint`, `animate`, `full-power`.

- `always` ‚Äî runs at any substrate tier
- `paint` ‚Äî runs at full/half/quarter; skip at paused
- `animate` ‚Äî runs at full/half; skip at quarter/paused
- `full-power` ‚Äî runs only at full

Defaults derived from `:perm` if not specified.

### :chip

Optional string. Auto-emit chip kind on successful dispatch. One of `paint.applied`, `motion.applied`, `look.changed`.

Zero per-verb code ‚Äî the dispatcher emits one chip envelope per accepted call when this is set.

## A.6 Alias and deprecation

### :deprecated

Boolean. If true, the verb still works but is not the preferred name. Doc typically prefixed with `[deprecated]`.

### :aliasFor

Optional string. If this verb is an alias, the canonical name it points to.

Together: `:deprecated #t :aliasFor \"cortex/write\"` means \"this verb still works but you should use cortex/write instead.\"

## A.7 Optional and reserved fields

### :examples-arc

Optional string. Pedagogical context ‚Äî a paragraph describing how the examples build on each other.

Used by teaching-oriented reference-manual renderers. Not part of the base introspection surface.

### Reserved fields

The following field names are reserved for future use and should not be added to verb records:

- `:body` ‚Äî the implementation function (never stored, always fetched from source)
- `:tests` ‚Äî test suite reference (planned, not yet standard)
- `:complexity` ‚Äî algorithmic complexity annotation (planned)
- `:examples-generated` ‚Äî LLM-generated examples that supplement `:examples`

## A.8 A worked SLAT record

Here is a complete verb record as SLAT:

```scheme
(verb
  :name        \"map\"
  :doc         \"Apply a procedure to each element of one or more lists, returning a new list of results.\"
  :contract    \"(procedure list ...) -> list\"
  :arity       variadic
  :examples
  ((:level novice       :code \"(map (lambda (x) (* x 2)) '(1 2 3))\")
   (:level intermediate :code \"(map + '(1 2 3) '(10 20 30))\")
   (:level expert       :code \"(map (lambda (kv) (cons (car kv) (* (cdr kv) 2))) alist)\"))
  :namespace   \"base\"
  :tier        \"core\"
  :perm        \"read\"
  :atom        \"list-op\"
  :source      \"src/base.js:77\"
  :since       \"1.0\"
  :confirm     #f
  :rateLimit   nil
  :idempotent  #t
  :powerTier   \"always\"
  :chip        nil
  :deprecated  #f
  :aliasFor    nil)
```

This is what the reference manual emits for `map`. Every verb has this same shape, with values that vary.

## A.9 Reading a record

Given a record, the reading workflow is:

1. **Read :doc.** One-sentence understanding.
2. **Read :contract.** Signature shape.
3. **Read :arity.** Argument count confirmation.
4. **Read :examples.** Working call templates.
5. **Read :perm.** Trust check.
6. **Read :tier.** Durability check.
7. **Read :source if needed.** Implementation reference.

Skim in order. Stop when you have what you need. Most calls stop at step 4.

## A.10 Generating a record

If you are registering a new verb, produce a record with at minimum these fields:

- `:name` (required)
- `:doc` (culturally required)
- `:contract` (culturally required)
- `:arity` (culturally required)
- `:examples` (at least one novice)
- `:perm` (required for state-changing verbs; inferred for reads)

The other fields are optional but recommended. `:namespace`, `:tier`, `:source`, `:since` all improve the introspection experience for downstream readers.

## A.11 The reference manual generator

`src/docs-emitter.js` walks the registry and emits one section per verb in this schema. The manual and the registry are consistent by construction ‚Äî the manual is a rendering of the registry, not a separate authoring source.

To regenerate the manual after adding a verb:

```scheme
(emit-reference-manual \"scheme/MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat\")
```

The manual updates. No drift.

## A.12 A field-quality checklist

For every verb you register:

- [ ] `:name` is unique in the registry
- [ ] `:doc` is imperative, one sentence, ends in period
- [ ] `:contract` accurately describes the intended shape
- [ ] `:arity` matches what the impl accepts
- [ ] `:examples` has at least one novice level
- [ ] `:perm` is explicit if the verb changes state
- [ ] `:namespace` is present if the verb has a prefix
- [ ] `:tier` is set (defaults to extended if unclear)
- [ ] `:source` points at the registration line
- [ ] `:since` records when the verb was added

Ten items. If your registration passes all ten, the verb is well-documented.

## A.13 The schema is stable

The field set has been frozen since Motoi 1.0. New fields (like `:powerTier`, `:chip`) have been added as additive extensions. Existing fields have not changed shape.

This stability matters because tools built on the schema keep working across releases. If you built a linter that reads `:perm`, that linter will still work in Motoi 2.0 because `:perm` is not going anywhere.

## A.14 A note on non-verb records

The reference manual also contains records for:

- Special forms (`define`, `lambda`, `let`, etc.) ‚Äî these have a subset of the fields
- Macros ‚Äî these have the verb schema plus a `:macro #t` marker
- Reader syntax (`#t`, `#f`, quote, etc.) ‚Äî minimal records with `:reader-syntax #t`

The verb schema is the base; other kinds are variants that add or omit fields as needed.

## A.15 Conclusion

The verb record schema is the alphabet the whole introspection layer is spelled in. Every field has a purpose. Every purpose has a consumer (REPL, reference manual, LLM training corpus, cart audit tools).

Fill in the fields. Every verb, every time. The reader on the other end will thank you.

## A.16 Field reference ‚Äî one-line summary

- `:name` ‚Äî registered name
- `:doc` ‚Äî one-sentence description
- `:contract` ‚Äî signature string
- `:arity` ‚Äî integer/list/variadic
- `:examples` ‚Äî tiered example list
- `:namespace` ‚Äî prefix grouping
- `:tier` ‚Äî core/extended/experimental
- `:perm` ‚Äî permission tier
- `:atom` ‚Äî fine-grained category
- `:source` ‚Äî path:line
- `:since` ‚Äî version tag
- `:confirm` ‚Äî dispatcher confirmation
- `:rateLimit` ‚Äî call frequency cap
- `:schema` ‚Äî argument validator
- `:idempotent` ‚Äî dedupe recent calls
- `:powerTier` ‚Äî substrate power gate
- `:chip` ‚Äî auto-emit chip kind
- `:deprecated` ‚Äî alias-only flag
- `:aliasFor` ‚Äî canonical name
- `:examples-arc` ‚Äî pedagogical context

Twenty fields. That is the whole verb record. Everything else in the introspection layer is a projection over these twenty.

## A.17 Compatibility notes

Older Motoi runtimes (pre-1.4) may not have `:powerTier` or `:chip`. Introspection over those fields returns nil. New tools should tolerate nil returns for these newer fields.

If you are writing a tool that must run across runtime versions, defensive coding is required:

```scheme
(or (cdr (assoc 'powerTier meta)) \"always\")
;; safe default if the field is missing
```

## A.18 SLAT rendering

When the reference manual renders a verb record as SLAT, the field order matches this appendix's schema. Reading the manual, you see fields in a predictable order every time.

When you author a verb record for the registry, order does not matter ‚Äî the registry is a map, not a list. But for readability in source, follow the schema order.

## A.19 The end

That is the schema. Twenty fields. One record per verb. One consistent shape across the whole language surface.

Next: Appendix B ‚Äî a printable cheat-sheet of introspection verbs.

## A.20 Field-by-field examples

Because concrete examples cement understanding, here is one worked record per field with commentary.

**`:name`** ‚Äî for `cortex/query`, the name is `\"cortex/query\"`. The slash is part of the name. Every character between the quotes is significant.

**`:doc`** ‚Äî for `cortex/query`, `\"Query Cortex records. Kwargs: :subject :predicate :object :at :source :order-by.\"` Notice: imperative (\"Query\"), one sentence, ends in period, names the kwargs.

**`:contract`** ‚Äî for `cortex/query`, `\"(:subject? :predicate? :object? :at? :source? :order-by?) -> list\"`. All kwargs are optional (marked with `?`). Returns a list of records.

**`:arity`** ‚Äî for `cortex/query`, `variadic` because kwargs mean any number of `:key value` pairs.

**`:examples`** ‚Äî for `cortex/query`, a list like:
```scheme
((:level novice :code \"(cortex/query :subject 'user)\")
 (:level intermediate :code \"(cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'preferred-color)\")
 (:level expert :code \"(cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'preferred-color :order-by 'at)\"))
```

**`:namespace`** ‚Äî `\"cortex\"`. The prefix before the slash.

**`:tier`** ‚Äî `\"core\"`. Frozen. Will not rename.

**`:perm`** ‚Äî `\"read\"`. Pure observation of Cortex records.

**`:atom`** ‚Äî `\"cortex-io\"`. Groups with `cortex/read` and `cortex/write`.

**`:source`** ‚Äî `\"lib/ai/cortex-io.js:121\"`. The line in the file where the verb is registered.

**`:since`** ‚Äî `\"1.0\"`. Has been there since day one.

## A.21 More on the schema fields not covered above

Every field in the schema has a purpose. If you did not know why a field exists, this section clarifies.

**`:confirm`** exists because some verbs are destructive enough that they should require the caller to have set a confirmation flag. Deleting cards, publishing to platforms, sending payments ‚Äî these are the kinds of things where accidental invocation is bad. The dispatcher checks `:confirm` and if true refuses to run unless `caller.confirmed` is set.

**`:rateLimit`** exists because some verbs make network calls or expensive computations. Rate-limiting prevents accidental spam. The format is `count/duration` where duration can be `s` (seconds), `min` (minutes), `hr` (hours), or `day`.

**`:schema`** is optional argument validation. A verb can attach a function that inspects its arguments before running. If the function returns anything other than `#t`, the dispatcher raises an error with that value as the message.

**`:idempotent`** is a performance hint. If a verb is a pure function of its input and expensive, marking it idempotent lets the dispatcher cache recent calls and skip re-invocation. Idempotence must be true; if the verb has hidden state, marking it idempotent will produce stale caches.

**`:powerTier`** gates against substrate power state. The substrate has a live power level (full, half, quarter, paused). A verb with `:powerTier animate` will be skipped when the substrate is at quarter or paused. This is how Motoi keeps animation loops from burning battery when the tab is backgrounded.

**`:chip`** is a display-tier convenience. If set, the dispatcher emits a small event envelope after successful dispatch. Chips are how UIs get real-time feedback that things happened without every verb needing to know about the UI.

## A.22 The manifest of what is and is not in the record

The verb record contains metadata. It does not contain:

- The implementation function itself (that lives in the source file)
- Tests (planned but not yet standard)
- Change history (git handles that)
- Author information (unless explicitly in the doc)
- Deployment status (managed elsewhere)

The record is intentionally lean. Everything on it is what a reader would want when they call `(help 'foo)`. Everything not on it is either tooling concern or living somewhere else with its own lifecycle.

## A.23 SLAT vs JSON

The reference manual emits SLAT. Some tooling around Motoi may render it as JSON for external consumers. The two are isomorphic ‚Äî every SLAT record maps to a JSON object with matching keys.

For internal Motoi tools, prefer SLAT. It macroexpands, it reads with source positions, it composes with the rest of the language.

For external tools (documentation sites, syntax highlighters, third-party editors), JSON is fine. `slat->json` and `json->slat` are the converters.

## A.24 A parting note

The verb record schema is old, in Motoi terms. It was set in the 1.0 release and has not changed in shape since. Every extension has been additive.

That stability is what lets you build tools on the schema without worrying about breakage. Every verb you introspect today has the same shape as every verb you will introspect in five years, minus additive fields that will only expand the answer, never change its interpretation.

Twenty fields. Same shape. Every verb. That is the schema.

Onward to Appendix B.

## A.25 A last set of examples

Three more full records, so you have variety.

**For `car`:**
```scheme
(verb :name \"car\" :doc \"Return the first element of a pair.\"
      :contract \"(pair) -> any\" :arity 1
      :examples ((:level novice :code \"(car '(1 2 3))\"))
      :namespace \"base\" :tier \"core\" :perm \"read\"
      :source \"src/base.js:73\" :since \"1.0\")
```

**For `paint-dot`:**
```scheme
(verb :name \"paint-dot\" :doc \"Draw a single pixel at coordinates.\"
      :contract \"(number number . color) -> nil\" :arity (2 3)
      :examples ((:level novice :code \"(paint-dot 10 20)\"))
      :namespace \"paint\" :tier \"core\" :perm \"paint\"
      :atom \"paint-primitive\" :powerTier \"paint\"
      :chip \"paint.applied\"
      :source \"src/paint.js:42\" :since \"1.0\")
```

**For `composer/slider`:**
```scheme
(verb :name \"composer/slider\" :doc \"Create a numeric slider bound to a target path.\"
      :contract \"(:label :bind :min :max :step . :orientation) -> slider-record\"
      :arity variadic
      :examples ((:level novice :code \"(composer/slider :label \\\"BPM\\\" :bind '(cart :bpm) :min 60 :max 240 :step 1)\"))
      :namespace \"composer\" :tier \"extended\" :perm \"state-change\"
      :atom \"composer-widget\"
      :source \"lib/composer/widgets.js:42\" :since \"1.4\")
```

Three verbs. Three complete records. Each one queryable via `(help 'name)`. Each one displayed in the reference manual with the same shape.

Onward to Appendix B ‚Äî the cheat-sheet.

## A.26 The schema is the language

The verb record schema is not just documentation. It is the language surface as data. Every tool built on top of Motoi's introspection layer ‚Äî the REPL, the reference manual, the training corpus generator, the audit scripts ‚Äî all read from this schema.

Learn the schema and you have learned the shape of Motoi's queryability.

Onward.
")
